snippet.textDisplay:
I have a problem with 5:50, and I would appreciate a woman's feedback with my issue.

I personally believe a healthy marriage is a co-operative marriage, where each partner is financially independent. Tiffany condescendingly said the men were all broke, with the crowd seemingly in agreement that she made the right choice, not to mess with a broke man. She wants a man with money.

Let's say, hypothetically, that there was a man with integrity and good credit—but in a financial stint (because that's more likely in today's age), or even a guy with bad credit still held the qualities he wanted (bad credit, nothing he can't turn around). Would she still turn him down?

Are women attracted to character first or income and ability to provide? I know our society has progressed so the idea that a man is supposed to be the sole provider is dying out, but is a woman still willing to take a chance with a man with little to no money—yet genuinely strives for God-given character? Or is a dude with money (skill to provide) more attractive? Even with a sub-par personalitity?

I'm just curious, and this gave me an excuse to write. I know some of y'all reading this have Masters and PhDs so I would appreciate the critical feedback.
